[src:supercompilation/automatic-programming] In computer science, **automatic programming** is a type of computer programming in which some mechanism generates a computer program, to allow human programmers to write the code at a higher abstraction level.
[src:supercompilation/automatic-programming] There has been little agreement on the precise definition of automatic programming, mostly because its meaning has changed over time.
[src:supercompilation/automatic-programming] David Parnas, tracing the history of "automatic programming" in published research, noted that in the 1940s it described automation of the manual process of punching paper tape.
[src:supercompilation/automatic-programming] Later it referred to translation of high-level programming languages like Fortran and ALGOL.
[src:supercompilation/automatic-programming] One of the earliest programs identifiable as a compiler is named Autocode.
[src:supercompilation/automatic-programming] Program synthesis is one type of automatic programming where a procedure is created from scratch, based on mathematical requirements.
[src:supercompilation/automatic-programming] Mildred Koss, an early UNIVAC programmer, explains: "Writing machine code involved several tedious steps—breaking down a process into discrete instructions, assigning specific memory locations to all the commands, and managing the I/O buffers.
[src:supercompilation/automatic-programming] After following these steps to implement mathematical routines, a sub-routine library, and sorting programs, our task was to look at the larger programming process.
[src:supercompilation/automatic-programming] We needed to understand how we might reuse tested code and have the machine help in programming.
[src:supercompilation/automatic-programming] As we programmed, we examined the process and tried to think of ways to abstract these steps to incorporate them into higher-level language.
[src:supercompilation/automatic-programming] The goal is to improve programmer productivity.
[src:supercompilation/automatic-programming] It is often related to code-reuse topics such as component-based software engineering.
[src:supercompilation/automatic-programming] Modern programming languages are well supported by tools like Json4Swift (Swift) and Json2Kotlin (Kotlin).
[src:supercompilation/automatic-programming] These application generators supported COBOL inserts and overrides.
[src:supercompilation/automatic-programming] A macro processor, such as the C preprocessor, which replaces patterns in source code according to relatively simple rules, is a simple form of source-code generator.
[src:supercompilation/automatic-programming] Source-to-source code generation tools also exist.
[src:supercompilation/automatic-programming] Large language models such as ChatGPT are capable of generating a program's source code from a description of the program given in a natural language.
[src:supercompilation/automatic-programming] Many relational database management systems (RDBMS) provide a function that will export the content of the database as SQL data definition queries, which may then be executed to re-import the tables and their data, or migrate them to another RDBMS.
[src:supercompilation/automatic-programming] Some languages use *annotations* to generate source code and inject it.
[src:supercompilation/automatic-programming] For example, this is done in Java and Kotlin using annotations, for example the Project Lombok library which runs at compile time with an annotation processor.
[src:supercompilation/automatic-programming] There has been a C++ proposal to add token sequence injection using compile-time reflective programming (reflection).
[src:supercompilation/automatic-programming] A low-code development platform (LCDP) is software that provides an environment programmers use to create application software through graphical user interfaces and configuration instead of traditional computer programming.
[src:supercompilation/automatic-programming] Vibe coding is a software development practice assisted by artificial intelligence (AI) where the software developer describes a project or task in a prompt to a large language model (LLM) which generates source code automatically.
[src:supercompilation/automatic-programming] Vibe coding may involve accepting AI-generated code without thorough review of the output, instead relying on results and follow-up prompts to guide changes.
[src:supercompilation/automatic-programming] The term was coined in February 2025 by computer scientist Andrej Karpathy, a co-founder of OpenAI and former AI leader at Tesla.
[src:supercompilation/automatic-programming] Merriam-Webster listed the term in March 2025 as a "slang & trending" expression.
[src:supercompilation/automatic-programming] It was named the *Collins English Dictionary* Word of the Year for 2025.
[src:supercompilation/automatic-programming] Advocates of vibe coding say that it allows even amateur programmers to produce software without the extensive training and skills required for software engineering.
[src:supercompilation/automatic-programming] Critics point out a lack of accountability, maintainability, and an increased risk of introducing security vulnerabilities in the resulting software.
[src:supercompilation/deforestation-computer-science] In the theory of programming languages in computer science, **deforestation** (also known as **fusion**) is a program transformation to eliminate intermediate lists or tree structures that are created and then immediately consumed by a program.
[src:supercompilation/deforestation-computer-science] The term "deforestation" was created by Philip Wadler, originally in his 1990 paper "Deforestation: transforming programs to eliminate trees".
[src:supercompilation/deforestation-computer-science] Deforestation is typically applied to programs in functional programming languages, more so non-strict programming languages such as Haskell.
[src:supercompilation/deforestation-computer-science] One algorithm for deforestation, named *shortcut deforestation*, is implemented in the Glasgow Haskell Compiler.
[src:supercompilation/deforestation-computer-science] Deforestation is closely related to escape analysis.
[src:supercompilation/loop-optimization] In compiler theory, **loop optimization** is the process of increasing execution speed and reducing the overheads associated with loops.
[src:supercompilation/loop-optimization] It plays an important role in improving cache performance and making effective use of parallel processing capabilities.
[src:supercompilation/loop-optimization] Most execution time of a scientific program is spent on loops; as such, many compiler optimization techniques have been developed to make them faster.
[src:supercompilation/loop-optimization] Since instructions inside loops can be executed repeatedly, it is frequently not possible to give a bound on the number of instruction executions that will be impacted by a loop optimization.
[src:supercompilation/loop-optimization] This presents challenges when reasoning about the correctness and benefits of a loop optimization, specifically the representations of the computation being optimized and the optimization(s) being performed.
[src:supercompilation/loop-optimization] Loop optimization can be viewed as the application of a sequence of specific **loop transformations** (listed below or in *Compiler transformations for high-performance computing*) to the source code or intermediate representation, with each transformation having an associated test for legality.
[src:supercompilation/loop-optimization] A transformation (or sequence of transformations) generally must preserve the temporal sequence of all dependencies if it is to preserve the result of the program (i.e., be a legal transformation).
[src:supercompilation/loop-optimization] Evaluating the benefit of a transformation or sequence of transformations can be quite difficult within this approach, as the application of one beneficial transformation may require the prior use of one or more other transformations that, by themselves, would result in reduced performance.
[src:supercompilation/loop-optimization] The unimodular transformation approach uses a single unimodular matrix to describe the combined result of a sequence of many of the above transformations.
[src:supercompilation/loop-optimization] Central to this approach is the view of the set of all executions of a statement within *n* loops as a set of integer points in an *n*-dimensional space, with the points being executed in lexicographical order.
[src:supercompilation/loop-optimization] For example, the executions of a statement nested inside an outer loop with index *i* and an inner loop with index *j* can be associated with the pairs of integers ⁠ $(i,j)$ ⁠.
[src:supercompilation/loop-optimization] The application of a unimodular transformation corresponds to the multiplication of the points within this space by the matrix.
[src:supercompilation/loop-optimization] For example, the interchange of two loops corresponds to the matrix ${\begin{bmatrix}0&1\\1&0\end{bmatrix}}$ .
[src:supercompilation/loop-optimization] A unimodular transformation is legal if it preserves the temporal sequence of all dependencies; measuring the performance impact of a unimodular transformation is more difficult.
[src:supercompilation/loop-optimization] Imperfectly nested loops and some transformations (such as tiling) do not fit easily into this framework.
[src:supercompilation/loop-optimization] The polyhedral model handles a wider class of programs and transformations than the unimodular framework.
[src:supercompilation/loop-optimization] The set of executions of a set of statements within a possibly imperfectly nested set of loops is seen as the union of a set of polytopes representing the executions of the statements.
[src:supercompilation/loop-optimization] Affine transformations are applied to these polytopes, producing a description of a new execution order.
[src:supercompilation/loop-optimization] The boundaries of the polytopes, the data dependencies, and the transformations are often described using systems of constraints, and this approach is often referred to as a **constraint-based** approach to loop optimization.
[src:supercompilation/loop-optimization] For example, a single statement within an outer loop 'for i := 0 to n' and an inner loop 'for j := 0 to i+2' is executed once for each (i, j) pair such that 0 <= i <= n and 0 <= j <= i+2.
[src:supercompilation/loop-optimization] Once again, a transformation is legal if it preserves the temporal sequence of all dependencies.
[src:supercompilation/loop-optimization] Estimating the benefits of a transformation, or finding the best transformation for a given code on a given computer, remain the subject of ongoing research as of the time of this writing (2010).
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] An **optimizing compiler** is a compiler designed to generate code that is optimized in aspects such as minimizing program execution time, memory usage, storage size, and power consumption.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Optimization is generally implemented as a sequence of **optimizing transformations**, a.k.a.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] **compiler optimizations** – algorithms that transform code to produce semantically equivalent code optimized for some aspect.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Optimization is limited by a number of factors.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Theoretical analysis indicates that some optimization problems are NP-complete, or even undecidable.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Also, producing perfectly *optimal* code is not possible since optimizing for one aspect often degrades performance for another (see: superoptimization).
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Optimization is a collection of heuristic methods for improving resource usage in typical programs.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Scope describes how much of the input code is considered to apply optimizations.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Local scope optimizations use information local to a basic block.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Since basic blocks contain no control flow statements, these optimizations require minimal analysis, reducing time and storage requirements.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] However, no information is retained across jumps.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Global scope optimizations, also known as intra-procedural optimizations, operate on individual functions.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] This gives them more information to work with but often makes expensive computations necessary.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Worst-case assumptions need to be made when function calls occur or global variables are accessed because little information about them is available.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Peephole optimizations are usually performed late in the compilation process after machine code has been generated.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] This optimization examines a few adjacent instructions (similar to "looking through a peephole" at the code) to see whether they can be replaced by a single instruction or a shorter sequence of instructions.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] For instance, a multiplication of a value by two might be more efficiently executed by left-shifting the value or by adding the value to itself (this example is also an instance of strength reduction).
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Interprocedural optimizations analyze all of a program's source code.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] The more information available, the more effective the optimizations can be.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] The information can be used for various optimizations, including function inlining, where a call to a function is replaced by a copy of the function body.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Link-time optimization (LTO), or whole-program optimization, is a more general class of interprocedural optimization.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] During LTO, the compiler has visibility across translation units which allows it to perform more aggressive optimizations like cross-module inlining and devirtualization.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Machine code optimization involves using an object code optimizer to analyze the program after all machine code has been linked.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Techniques such as macro compression, which conserves space by condensing common instruction sequences, become more effective when the entire executable task image is available for analysis.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Most high-level programming languages share common programming constructs and abstractions, such as branching constructs (if, switch), looping constructs (for, while), and encapsulation constructs (structures, objects).
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Thus, similar optimization techniques can be used across languages.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] However, certain language features make some optimizations difficult.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] For instance, pointers in C and C++ make array optimization difficult; see alias analysis.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] However, languages such as PL/I that also support pointers implement optimizations for arrays.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Conversely, some language features make certain optimizations easier.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] For example, in some languages, functions are not permitted to have side effects.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Therefore, if a program makes several calls to the same function with the same arguments, the compiler can infer that the function's result only needs to be computed once.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] In languages where functions are allowed to have side effects, the compiler can restrict such optimization to functions that it can determine have no side effects.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Many optimizations that operate on abstract programming concepts (loops, objects, structures) are independent of the machine targeted by the compiler, but many of the most effective optimizations are those that best exploit special features of the target platform.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Examples are instructions that do several things at once, such as decrement register and branch if not zero.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] The following is an instance of a local machine-dependent optimization.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] To set a register to 0, the obvious way is to use the constant '0' in an instruction that sets a register value to a constant.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] A less obvious way is to XOR a register with itself or subtract it from itself.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] It is up to the compiler to know which instruction variant to use.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] On many RISC machines, both instructions would be equally appropriate, since they would both be the same length and take the same time.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] A potential problem with this is that XOR or subtract may introduce a data dependency on the previous value of the register, causing a pipeline stall, which occurs when the processor must delay execution of an instruction because it depends on the result of a previous instruction.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] However, processors often treat the XOR of a register with itself or the subtract of a register from itself as a special case that does not cause stalls.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Whether particular optimizations can and should be applied may depend on the characteristics of the target machine.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] parameterize machine-dependent factors so that they can be used to optimize for different machines.
