[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Interprocedural optimization works on the entire program, across procedure and file boundaries.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] It works tightly with intraprocedural counterparts, carried out with the cooperation of a local part and a global part.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Typical interprocedural optimizations are procedure inlining, interprocedural dead-code elimination, interprocedural constant propagation, and procedure reordering.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] As usual, the compiler needs to perform interprocedural analysis before its actual optimizations.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Interprocedural analyses include alias analysis, array access analysis, and the construction of a call graph.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Interprocedural optimization is common in modern commercial compilers from SGI, Intel, Microsoft, and Sun Microsystems.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] For a long time, the open source GCC was criticized for a lack of powerful interprocedural analysis and optimizations, though this is now improving.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Another open-source compiler with full analysis and optimization infrastructure is Open64.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Due to the extra time and space required by interprocedural analysis, most compilers do not perform it by default.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Users must use compiler options explicitly to tell the compiler to enable interprocedural analysis and other expensive optimizations.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] There can be a wide range of optimizations that a compiler can perform, ranging from simple and straightforward optimizations that take little compilation time to elaborate and complex optimizations that involve considerable amounts of compilation time.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] By the 2000s, it was common for compilers, such as Clang, to have several compiler command options that could affect a variety of optimization choices, starting with the familiar `-O2` switch.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] An approach to isolating optimization is the use of so-called post-pass optimizers (some commercial versions of which date back to mainframe software of the late 1970s).
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] These tools take the executable output by an optimizing compiler and optimize it even further.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Post-pass optimizers usually work on the assembly language or machine code level (in contrast with compilers that optimize intermediate representations of programs).
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] One such example is the Portable C Compiler (PCC) of the 1980s, which had an optional pass that would perform post-optimizations on the generated assembly code.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Another consideration is that optimization algorithms are complicated and, especially when being used to compile large, complex programming languages, can contain bugs that introduce errors in the generated code or cause internal errors during compilation.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Compiler errors of any kind can be disconcerting to the user, but especially so in this case, since it may not be clear that the optimization logic is at fault.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] In the case of internal errors, the problem can be partially ameliorated by a "fail-safe" programming technique in which the optimization logic in the compiler is coded such that a failure is trapped, a warning message issued, and the rest of the compilation proceeds to successful completion.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Early compilers of the 1960s were often primarily concerned with simply compiling code correctly or efficiently, such that compile times were a major concern.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] One notable early optimizing compiler was the IBM FORTRAN H compiler of the late 1960s.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] Another of the earliest and important optimizing compilers, that pioneered several advanced techniques, was that for BLISS (1970), which was described in *The Design of an Optimizing Compiler* (1975).
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] By the late 1980s, optimizing compilers were sufficiently effective that programming in assembly language declined.
[src:supercompilation/optimizing-compiler] This co-evolved with the development of RISC chips and advanced processor features such as superscalar processors, out-of-order execution, and speculative execution, which were designed to be targeted by optimizing compilers rather than by human-written assembly code.
[src:supercompilation/program-transformation] A **program transformation** is any operation that takes a computer program and generates another program.
[src:supercompilation/program-transformation] In many cases the transformed program is required to be semantically equivalent to the original, relative to a particular formal semantics and in fewer cases the transformations result in programs that semantically differ from the original in predictable ways.
[src:supercompilation/program-transformation] While the transformations can be performed manually, it is often more practical to use a program transformation system that applies specifications of the required transformations.
[src:supercompilation/program-transformation] Program transformations may be specified as automated procedures that modify compiler data structures (e.g. abstract syntax trees) representing the program text, or may be specified more conveniently using patterns or templates representing parameterized source code fragments.
[src:supercompilation/program-transformation] A practical requirement for source code transformation systems is that they be able to effectively process programs written in a programming language.
[src:supercompilation/program-transformation] The problem of building and integrating adequate front ends for conventional languages (Java, C++, PHP etc.) may be of equal difficulty as building the program transformation system itself because of the complexity of such languages.
[src:supercompilation/program-transformation] To be widely useful, a transformation system must be able to handle many target programming languages, and must provide some means of specifying such language-specific front-ends.
[src:supercompilation/program-transformation] Spoon is an example of a Java-specific program transformation library that addresses this challenge by providing a full front-end for Java, exposing an AST-based API for implementing analyses and transformations of Java source code.
[src:supercompilation/program-transformation] In other words, a refinement of a program is *more defined* and *more deterministic* than the original program.
[src:supercompilation/program-transformation] If two programs are refinements of each other, then the programs are equivalent.
